Vice President Mike Pence visited the University of South Carolina to discuss the response to the coronavirus pandemic. He expressed gratitude for the state's efforts in combating the virus and emphasized the administration's commitment to providing testing, personal protective equipment, and therapeutics to South Carolina. Pence also praised the state's efforts to reopen schools and emphasized the importance of getting children back in the classroom. He acknowledged the rise in cases in the state but stated that the country is in a better position to respond to the pandemic than before. Pence encouraged individuals, particularly young people, to practice personal hygiene, wear masks, and follow local guidance. He also addressed concerns about the safety of reopening schools and assured parents that the risk to children is low. Pence pledged continued support and resources for states and emphasized the importance of working together to slow the spread of the virus.